defaultSummarydefault1. Technical solutions such as lessons about online s
defaultafety in computing classes and internet controls are by themselves insufficient to protect children and young people. A broad and comprehensive programme of sex and relationships education (SRE) in school is essential to ensure that children and young peop
defaultle get accurate information about sex and sexual health and an understanding of what constitutes respectful relationships.  This has been recognised in numerous reports including by 
defaultOfsted
default and the Office of the Children’s Commissioner. 
default2. A broad programm
defaulte of good quality SRE should also address the issue of on-line safety and pornography. This can complement the more technical learning about safety gained through computing classes. 
default3. Currently the provision of SRE in schools is unacceptably patchy and i
defaultnconsistent.
default 
defaultEvery child and young person has a right to comprehensive SRE and we (as adults) have a duty to ensure this.  
default&#xa0;default4. 
defaultThe best way to ensure this is by making SRE (within Personal, Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education) 
defaultcompulsory
default for prim
defaultary and secondary schools, and for teachers to receive training on the subject. 
defaultThe Government guidance on SRE should also be updated to provide clarity to schools.  
default  
default&#xa0;
default5. The majority of parents want SRE to be compulsory in schools and many would also li
defaultke support to fulfil their role at home as educators about growing up, safety, sex and relationships.
default6. Our evidence submission to this inquiry covers: 
default&#xa0;defaultWhat is SRE and how can it address online safety?default&#xa0;
default7. SRE involves learning about the emotional, social and physical aspects of growing up, relationships, human sexuality, sex and sexual health. It should equip children and young people with the information, skills and positive values to enable them to hav
defaulte safe, fulfilling relationships and to take responsibility for their sexual health and wellbeing. 
