default11. 
defaultAt primary school classes should start with discussing diff
defaulterences between boys and girls bodies, and the importance of loving and respectful relationships. Learning correct names for genitalia is important so that children have the language to describe their bodies, understand what behaviour would be abusive and 
defaultreport it if it happens to them. At secondary level lessons can look at ‘
defaultsexting
default’ and pressures from peers and make more direct reference to pornography in the context of learning about consent, body image, gender roles and respectful relationships. 
default12. H
defaultaving a basic universal language about respect, our bodies, growing up and sex is essential to support children with the words needed to report abuse and the belief that it is ‘OK to talk about this’.  
defaultWhat is the standard of SRE in schools today?default13
default.Ofsted
default inspectors report that SRE is currently inadequate in a third of schools (2013).
default Young people have repeatedly said that the SRE they receive is inadequate – with 28% describing their school SRE as ‘bad’ or ‘very bad’ in a survey in 2011 (Sex Educ
defaultation Forum). Young people say that the relationships aspect of SRE is the most neglected
default (Sex Education Forum 2008)
default.
default default14. 
defaultOfsted
default 
defaultconsulted pupils for their recent PSHE report ‘Not yet good enough’ (2013) and consequently 
defaultrecommended that schools address p
defaultornography within SRE
default. New research with young people carried out by Brook (2013 unpublished: also being submitted to this inquiry) shows that young people want 
defaultyoung people need better, more inclusive education on internet safety, both for children and fo
defaultr parents, 
defaultnot least 
defaultto ensure that knowledge, skills and understanding around online safety are embedded in the next generati
defaulton. 
default15. 
defaultOfsted
default are also concerned that some primary schools are failing to teach the basic body science that is necessary to unde
defaultrpin further learning about bodily privacy and safety. They found: “
defaultyounger pupils had not always learnt the correct names for sexual body parts
default” and see this as a safeguarding failure because it leaves children without the language skills to understand th
defaulteir bodies, know what is acceptable / unacceptable and to say what has happened to them (2013).
default&#xa0;defaultWhat is the evidence that SRE works? default&#xa0;default16. National and international research shows that good quality SRE has a protective function as young people who have good SRE are more likely to choose to have sex for the first time later, more likely to use contraception and to have fewer sexual partne
defaultrs (Kirby 2007, UNESCO 2009 and NICE 2010). 
default17. A comprehensive 
defaultprogramme
default of SRE also results in young people being less likely to have an ‘age-discrepant’ partner (Lindberg 2012). 
defaultHaving an older partner is a significant risk factor for experiencing phys
defaultical, emotional and sexual violence (for girls) – and a risk for sexual exploitation
default (Barter, 2009). 
default18. There is also evidence that SRE is more effective if home and school are involved (Kirby 2007 and see 
defaultEmmerson
default 2011). Parents are overwhelmingly suppo
defaultrtive of SRE and a recent survey shows that 83% of parents want SRE lessons to cover issues relating to pornography (NAHT, 2013 and see also 
defaultMumsnet
default 2011).  
default19. SRE aims to contribute to behavior change, including reducing unprotected and unwanted sex, an
defaultd reducing harmful 
defaultbehaviour
default, including sexual offences such as assault and abuse. 
default&#xa0;
default20. Good SRE, together with access to sexual health services will contribute to several public health priorities that are essential for the health and well-being of the na
defaulttion, and especially to women:  
